e Characters]]'' (1971)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actress]]\n* [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Berlinale}}\n* [http://www.berlinale.de Berlinale website]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000091/2015 Berlin Film Festival at IMDb]\n\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actress}}\n{{Berlin International Film Festival}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver Bear For Best Actress}}\n[[Category:Berlin International Film Festival]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actress winners| ]]\n[[Category:Film awards for lead actress]]\n[[Category:Awards for actresses]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by award|Silver Bear, Best Actress]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Silver Bear for Best Actress''' ({{lang-de|Silberner B\u00e4r/Beste Darstellerin}}) is the [[Berlin International Film Festival]]'s award for achievement in performance by an [[actress]]. It is selected by the jury of the festival for films in the official competition slate. \n\nThe award was first presented in 1956, and can be for lead or supporting roles. The award was not presented in 1969, 1970, 1973, 1974, and 1990. [[Sachiko Hidari]] is the only actress who won the award for two films in the 1964 competition. In 2011, the award was given to the entire female cast of ''[[A Separation]]''. [[Shirley MacLaine]] is the only actress that has won the award more than once.\n\n==Award winners==\n[[File:Elsa Martinelli 1964.JPG|thumb|150px|alt= photo of Elsa Martinelli|[[Elsa Martinelli]], the first winner of the Berlin Film Festival Award for Best Actress.]][[File:Elizabeth Taylor-1954.JPG|thumb|150px|alt= photo of Elizabeth Taylor|[[Elizabeth Taylor]], winner of the 1972 Berlin Film Festival Award for Best Actress.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Table key\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"height:20px; width:30px\" | \u2020\n| Indicates the performance was also an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] '''winner'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"height:20px; width:30px\" | \u